The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A portion of the airport?s boundary wall collapsed during a storm on Tuesday. CISF commandant Sanjay Prakash said additional personnel had been posted on the spot where the wall collapsed.

 In another development, the special security check-points on the roads approaching the airport were wound up on Tuesday. The CISF, however, will continue to look after security on the airport premises. 

 Power cuts early on Tuesday plunged the operating theatres and some other departments at National Medical College and Hospital into darkness. Several scheduled operations had to be cancelled. Supply resumed around 10.30 am.

 The Centre has sanctioned Rs 5 crore for the upgrade of the Kalighat temple complex, state tourism secretary T.K. Burman said on Tuesday. The project cost is Rs 15 crore. The remaining amount will be raised from private companies, NGOs and NRIs. 

 Train services on the Sealdah-Bongaon section were disrupted twice on Tuesday afternoon. First, an overhead wire snapped, leading to the cancellation of three local trains. That prompted a group of passengers to block the tracks at Dum Dum Cantonment station. The blockade, which continued for around 40 minutes from 11 am, was lifted after officials pacified the protesters. 

 Three persons were injured in a road mishap in Salt Lake on Tuesday afternoon. Police said a private bus on route 215A rammed into the PNB island after the driver lost control. The driver has been arrested.

 Army jawan Chintamoni G. was killed when a bullet from his service weapon went through his forehead at Bengal Army headquarters, on AJC Bose Road, on Tuesday morning. Police suspect the 29-year-old jawan had committed suicide. 

 A man, identified as Kochi, was arrested in Tollygunge on Monday after a revolver and six cartridges were found in his possession. Police said Kochi was the right-hand man of Swapan De, a criminal of south Calcutta.

